CZ7E67lfJ4fuZDmLHasfpr3L563XbcgyBKSwTIhAON-ANSG8vDyuOvel4PAk06tWnTpPxGN_sU2=
KqR1PtUO96G3Af4URTw-aSNwVtiZ_SpCONNFUU7h988x0CCdo3CR1pTIkgk8EIdhItA0nmggez7=
6e2PJaImJMU0jG2yc2hZefx8S3c2k8TLKTVN45Dr2Y54W0LmL7hoOuJBkribX9DItdg ). More=
 broadly, though, this entire release feels like a consumer product release=
: yes, the underlying model is better, but its not GPT-5, and that=E2=80=99=
s not the focus; the real improvements are in the user experience and the a=
ctual ChatGPT product. That is what it takes to win in consumer, to a much =
greater extent than enterprise.

Moreover, this approach seems in-line with an Apple partnership. I mentione=
d the hardware limitation earlier; as fast as GPT-4o appears to be, there i=
s still the hassle of taking out your phone, unlocking it, launching an app=
, and entering voice mode; what if that functionality was available in the =
same way Siri is available today?

On the flipside, what does Apple have to offer ChatGPT? Distribution is cer=
tainly massive, and Apple may be paying for access; they also provide a ver=
y wide funnel to premium ChatGPT memberships. At the same time they are als=
o a company with a lot of cash: is OpenAI=E2=80=99s sudden dramatic increas=
e in inference capabilities purely a function of model improvement, or is A=
pple paying up to make sure that ChatGPT is more performant than ever, to t=
he extent that it is actually a viable alternative to Google=E2=80=99s Gemi=
ni for Apple=E2=80=99s needs?

I don=E2=80=99t know the answers to all of these questions; some will be an=
swered today at Google I/O, some next week at Microsoft Build, and some in =
June at WWDC. What is clear is that OpenAI is fully committed to ensuring i=
t plays a role in whatever comes next.

